		{"id":"0c1358a66bfff4bb","type":"text","text":"TEMPLATE","x":5185,"y":-1618,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"6add5cd6ff6f2e85","type":"file","file":"Sims4-Yootz-Story/spoilers/Fairy draining.md","x":3790,"y":840,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"300c2626ca18126a","type":"file","file":"Sims4-Yootz-Story/spoilers/Draining schedule.md","x":4255,"y":840,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"1abff541c426e51f","type":"file","file":"Sims4-Yootz-Story/spoilers/Transform despite draining.md","x":4720,"y":840,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"3d020125b954c117","type":"file","file":"Sims4-Yootz-Story/spoilers/First full moon.md","x":5650,"y":840,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"50cee51360d4a252","type":"file","file":"Sims4-Yootz-Story/spoilers/More advice.md","x":5185,"y":840,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"646b37c439be0cf7","type":"text","text":"Possibly after the full moon, because I'm thinking that even the fairy can't stop her from transforming during the full moon. The wolf might be especially violent that full moon after basically being bottled up for a little while, but I'm thinking she comes away from that transformation even less in favor of the draining. Maybe she doesn't have words for it, but on some level she can feel what the wolf wants.","x":6320,"y":780,"width":440,"height":234},
		{"id":"1e7d71ac66aadf73","type":"text","text":"I guess I'm picturing it like kind of comparing the wolf's rampage to a toddler's tantrum. And after it has its way and fights and fights and wears itself out, inside her it feels like the wolf is cuddled up napping instead of clawing at her. Because the wolf isn't a monster. It has will, but that doesn't mean it has ill will. It's not against her, it feels like it's needs are not getting met. That's why it's ranging the way it is. It doesn't like being suppressed and ignored and drowned out. It just wants to feel heard. And I'm thinking on some level, her and the vampire sort of get it? Also as far as the transforming despite the schedule, I'm taking maybe that happens shortly before the full moon, and the vampire can sense that the wolf magic is changing as the full moon Rose closer and it's not going to be malleable with the ferry magic. Like they know that her transforming is coming. Like I mean they're not totally 100% certain about literally everything, but at least the vampire grandmother can sense that yeah this is probably going to go this way. The wolf magic is changing with the moon. I'm also thinking that transforming despite following the draining schedule is a particularly rough draining for the werewolf. Because the wolf is getting pissed about its needs not being met, and the Moon is filling so it's getting more powerful, and I'm thinking she starts to shift or she does shift and then the ferry comes in and drains her, and that's like physically really hard on her. Like yeah the drainings in general are not great, but like that one's especially bad, and it leaves the wolf especially pissed. Like that draining session is either one of the worst ones or the worst one. And she can feel what the wolf feels about it. And the vampire can at sort of feels it too. I'm not really picturing it as a teenager setting a hard line in the sand, I'm not picturing her just being like no we're not draining me anymore no matter what. I'm not picturing her being that assertive about it. Again she feels exhausted she feels drained, and she doesn't fully understand it herself. She's new to this whole being werewolf thing, and she still not fully understanding the wolf inside of her. And as far as how they get towards the more mindfulness-based strategy, I'm thinking that on some level in some way between these events, the grandmother starts to be reminded of her own anger, her own hot headed temper. Like the Wolf starts reminding her for anger in some ways. Or she sees the wolf as being angry like herself? I'm not exactly sure again it's one of those things it's not going to translate into words quite right, but I'm picturing the grandmother sitting down and talking to the teenager and being like basically maybe we try what works for my anger or something like that. And that's how they get towards more of the mindfulness type of strategy. Instead of trying to suppress and starve the wolf essentially, give it what it needs. It becomes shifting away from trying to forcibly control the wolf against its will to making peace with it. It's not a game of tug of war, it's a matter of working together. ","x":6880,"y":780,"width":459,"height":344},
		{"id":"c221ebe477f1adc0","type":"file","file":"Sims4-Yootz-Story/spoilers/Adult.md","x":8345,"y":2440,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"f8cc27e0e2fbc3e7","type":"file","file":"Sims4-Yootz-Story/spoilers/Cure.md","x":7880,"y":2440,"width":400,"height":400}
	],
